### How did we achieve distribution?
Master is initialized with total_work and work_unit. Total work refers to the entire range of the values that the program needs to add to the prefix to generate input string, and work_unit refers to the number of sub-problems that a worker gets in a single request from the master. On the server-side, the work is distributed in a dynamic fashion where, every time a worker is finished with their assigned task, a new subrange of total_work of the size equal to work_unit is assigned by the master to the worker. On the client-side, the distribution of the work is static. When a worker is done with its computation, it doesn’t need to contact the master as it has already been assigned with all the subranges at the start. These subranges are again of length work_unit. There is, however, a hole in this design. Whenever a worker fails or doesn’t respond, all of its progress is lost.

The above architecture works well for an individual system but is susceptible to performing duplicate work, which would be deemed redundant. This is because each system will loop over the same range of values. For every client and the server to work on different input strings, we have appended systemIdentifier to our input string. systemIdentifier is a randomly generated string that aims to identify the device. Hence, the input string is in the following form:
```
inputString = prefix + ";" + systemIdentifier + count
```
